{"id":14881714,"mediaExerciseId":"66a6ce39-73e3-481e-95a6-3410cec31aef","exerciseName":"4","chapterName":"20","chapterTitle":"Credit and Inventory Management","groupId":612458,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":700,"solutions":[{"id":6041811,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we need to list the five Cs of credit and  to explain the importance of each. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The five Cs of credit are character, capacity, capital, collateral, and conditions. \n\n**Character** is important because it gives us information on whether the client is ready to settle his credit obligations.\n\n**Capacity** is the creditworthiness of a client to settle liabilities using operating money.\n\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"**Capital** gives us data on the amount of money the client has in the name of financial reserves.\n\n**Collateral** gives us information about the funds pledged by the client (as a mortgage) in case he does not fulfill his obligation to pay for the goods under the agreed conditions.\n\nThe **Conditions** give us information about the general economic conditions in the client's business.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"63b1188e-7dec-4ed0-8f57-52c8b271cb91","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd